@NODE requi "Requirements"

This program requires an Amiga, Workbench 2+ and some internet s/w :)

@ENDNODE

@NODE insta "Installation"

Simple: Copy it wherever you like :)

@ENDNODE

@NODE prefs "Prefs"

Before you do anything else with NetMenu, first go into the REXX drawer
and edit any of the ARexx scripts contained within for the internet
s/w you are using. The ones supplied are for:

 * Miami
 * IBrowse
 * AmIRC
 * GUI-FTP
 
For each package you use, it is a good idea to make an arexx script that
does each of the following (where possible):

 * Does any operations needed when starting the package
 * Quits the package
 
When you have all the correct ARexx scripts, load up netmenu. From the main
window, go to the "Prefs" menu item (shortcut: Amiga-P). This should
bring up the preferences window. Now click on "TCP Prefs" to set up your
TCP/IP software (AmiTCP, Miami etc.). This should open up a window with
3 string gadgets:

 Load TCP
 TCP Arexx
 Shut TCP
 
In the first, put the path and filename of your TCP client (e.g.
dh1:AmiTCP/AmiTCP). In the second, put the name of the arexx script
you wrote to be executed on startup (the included example iconifies Miami),
and in the third pit the name of the arexx script to shut down the TCP
s/w. Note that the last two are optional.

Now click on close. If you now click on WWW prefs, you should get a similar
window. All of the gadgets mean the same thing, but for your browser
software. Fill those in and do the same for IRC, FTP and EMail.

Click on "Dial Prefs", and this should open up a window with the following
string gadgets:

 Online Arexx:
 Offline Arexx:
 
These are simply the path and names of arexx scripts to tell your TCP program
to go online/offline.

Now click on "Save Prefs", and then on "Close". Now quit netmenu, and load
it again.

NEW for v1.1: When you click on "Save Prefs", NetMenu also stores the x
and y positions of the main window, and the next time you run it, the
window will appear where you left it!

@ENDNODE

@NODE custo "Using custom samples"

Simply replace the sample in the samples/ draw with the RAW sample of your
choice. Then load up NetMenu, and go into the prefs window. Now click on
"Sound Prefs" and click on "Test" for the sample you replaced. If it sounds
too high, move the slider gadget to the left, if it sounds too low, move
the slider gadget to the right. When all the samples are ok, click on "Close"
then on "Save Prefs" and then on "Close" and thats all you need to do!

@ENDNODE

@NODE usage "Usage"

Once NetMenu has been configured, all you have to do is click "Online"
to go online, "Offline" to go offline, "FTP" to load your FTP s/w, "IRC"
to load your IRC software, "WWW" to load your browser and "EMail" to
load your Email software.

@ENDNODE

